<paragraph blockId="59.[151,1436,151,321]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
We detected the clypeus trilobate, eyes mid-sized and glabrous, the dorsal pronotal area with posterior pronotal sulcus foveolate, and with humeral angle not projected, the mesoscuto-scutellar suture sulcate, the metanotum undeveloped medially, the wings are fully developed, the forewings with three closed cells (C 
<subScript attach="both" box="[1182,1190,241,255]" fontSize="6" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">2</subScript>
c, R 
<subScript attach="both" box="[1234,1242,241,255]" fontSize="6" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">2</subScript>
c, 1Cu 
<subScript attach="right" box="[1314,1322,241,255]" fontSize="6" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">2</subScript>
c), and the metapostnotal median carina is long. All of these observations support the placement of this species in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kieffer" authorityYear="1904" box="[1303,1413,259,285]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Holepyris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1303,1413,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Holepyris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
